column169: On February 3, 2025, one (1) 330-gallon tote of phosphoric acid was punctured and released approximately 330-gallons of product to the asphalt pavement and nearby storm drain. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Thin Line Environmental (TLE) to remediate the impacted site. TLE personnel noted that the product released into a storm drain onsite and began utilizing a vacuum trailer to remove the liquids at each storm drain between the terminal building and the retention pond. All acid impacted liquids were collected and containerized into three (3) 330-gallon totes and one (1) 275-gallon tote and staged onsite for further management.

A fiberboard box with signs of a release was discovered during sort operations at the MEMH location. The fiberboard box contained a single plastic bottle that was packaged in a paper envelope with bubble wrap for dunnage. The cap on the plastic bottle was loose causing a release of the contents. The shipment was placed into a steel salvage package and a new declaration will be obtained for movement.

On February 12, 2025, one (1) 600-pound pressurized tank of UN3500 was crushed in transit and released approximately 5-ounces of product to the dock floor and pallet. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental (FCE) to remediate the impacted site. FCE personnel utilized hand tools and absorbents to remediate the UN3500-impacted loading dock floor. After remediating the product released on the pallet and loading dock, the crew utilized a forklift to move the leaking tank into an open well ventilated area. The damaged tank was labeled with a non-haz waste label and all impacted material was collected and containerized into two (2) 55-gallon drums.

column169: ABF Operation Supervisor Teddy Trautwein states that all the employees went to break at the same time and while they were on break, a 55 gallon drum of UN1263, Paint, 3 Unknown PG began to leak in the storage area near dock door 43. ABF Supervisor states that the puncture looks to be from a forklift  blade but none of his workers have owned up to it yet. Safety advised that we would need to know the forklift operator ASAP if he finds out and to pull CCTV video to find the suspect. Teddy emailed ABF Hazmat stating that one of his employees, Trevor Story, may have accidentally punctured the drum while trying to off load a hazmat tote from dock door 52 that's awaiting billing. Safety responded stating that we'll need to pull some CCTV to confirm this but he's currently a possible source of the spill. ABF Supervisor states that hazmat pro 069559511 was involved in the spill so Safety contacte d ABF069 and spoke with Supervisor Ronald Thompson and he clarified that the shipment only got paint on the shrink wrap and was not actively leaking.

XPO contacted ERTS regarding a smoking and leaking tote containing hazardous material, Ethylenediamine. A contractor dispatched and observed an estimated 1-ounce release onto the top of a tote from a defective bung cap. Upon further investigation, the contractor determined that the seal on the cap was damaged along with the threads. They replaced the cap and performed a slosh test. The tote passed and will ship on to the Consignee. No waste was generated from the incident. No storm-drains, waterways or soil were involved.

column43: MATCHES, SAFETY (BOOK, CARD OR STRIKE ON BOX
column169: Unload managers noticed that a plastic bubble-mailer envelope recently placed on the IC belt in the unload was smoking. A manager ripped it open and found that the package contained six boxes of safety matches. One of the boxes had caught on fire. The manager blew out the fire and alerted the DG Nav specialist, who was in the middle of processing hazmats. DG Nav specialist isolated the damaged package on a metal rack where it could not spread fire if it were to catch on fire again. The matches in the one box appear to be mostly or fully "used" given the burnt appearance. The other five boxes are in acceptable condition.
